content.problemStatement:
In C++, a union is a user-defined data type that allows you to store different types of data in the same memory location. \
Similar to structures, unions provide a way to create a composite data type, but unlike structures, all members of a union share the same memory space. \
This means that a union can hold only one value at a time, and the memory occupied by a union is equal to the size of its largest member.

**Declaration:**:
- To declare a `union`, you use the union keyword followed by the union's name and a list of member variables enclosed in curly braces. 
- Each member can be of a different data type. 
- Syntax as follows
```cpp
union MyUnion {
    int intValue;
    float floatValue;
    char charValue;
};
```

**Initialization:**
- Unions are initialized similarly to structures. 
- You can initialize a union by directly assigning values to its member
- Syntax as follows
```cpp
MyUnion u;
u.intValue = 42;
```

**Accessing Members:**
- Since all members share the same memory location, you can access only one member at a time.
- Accessing a different member will overwrite the existing value.
- Syntax as follows
```cpp
u.floatValue = 3.14;
cout << "Float Value: " << u.floatValue << "\n";
```

